04719nam a22007695i 9780231544573DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016046839  a(OCoLC)984657523  a97802315445737 a10.7312/milg175982doi  a(DE-B1597)482786  a(OCoLC)969973847  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHF5476b.M549 2017 7aBUS0790002bisacsh04a381.1701  aQH 4302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141581:1 aMilgrom, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscovering Prices :bAuction Design in Markets with Complex Constraints /cPaul Milgrom. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKenneth J. Arrow Lecture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. (Near-)Substitutes, Prices, and Stability -- t3. Vickrey Auctions and Substitution -- t4. Deferred-Acceptance Auctions and Near-Substitutes -- t5. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditional economic theory studies idealized markets in which prices alone can guide efficient allocation, with no need for central organization. Such models build from Adam Smith’s famous concept of an invisible hand, which guides markets and renders regulation or interference largely unnecessary. Yet for many markets, prices alone are not enough to guide feasible and efficient outcomes, and regulation alone is not enough, either. Consider air traffic control at major airports. While prices could encourage airlines to take off and land at less congested times, prices alone do just part of the job; an air traffic control system is still indispensable to avoid disastrous consequences. With just an air traffic controller, however, limited resources can be wasted or poorly used. What’s needed in this and many other real-world cases is an auction system that can effectively reveal prices while still maintaining enough direct control to ensure that complex constraints are satisfied.In Discovering Prices, Paul Milgrom—the world’s most frequently cited academic expert on auction design—describes how auctions can be used to discover prices and guide efficient resource allocations, even when resources are diverse, constraints are critical, and market-clearing prices may not even exist. Economists have long understood that externalities and market power both necessitate market organization. In this book, Milgrom introduces complex constraints as another reason for market design. Both lively and technical, Milgrom roots his new theories in real-world examples (including the ambitious U.S. incentive auction of radio frequencies, whose design he led) and provides economists with crucial new tools for dealing with the world’s growing complex resource allocation problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuction theory. 0aAuctionsxMathematical models. 0aPricesxMathematical models. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/milg1759840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544573.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK